<section xml:id="sec-10-2parametric-questions">
  <title>10.2 Parametric Equations</title>

  <exercises xml:id="parametric-curves">

  <introduction>
    <p>The following exercises review ideas from Section 10.2 on parametric equations, including identifying the curve, 
      determining direction of motion, recognizing repeated tracing, 
      and comparing different parametrizations of the same geometric object.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <exercise xml:id="ex-parametric-conceptual-1">
    <title> Exercise 1: Around the Circle</title>
    <statement>
      <p>A particle moves according to <m>x=\cos t</m>, <m>y=\sin t</m>, for <m>0\le t\le 4\pi</m>. 
        How many times is the unit circle traced?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement> <p>One-half time</p></statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
        <statement>  <p>One time</p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
        <statement>  <p>Two times</p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
      <statement>    <p>Four times</p> </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    <solution>
      <p>The parametrization <m>x=\cos t,\ y=\sin t</m> completes one full revolution when <m>t</m> runs from <m>0</m> to <m>2\pi</m>. 
        Since the interval is <m>0\le t\le 4\pi</m>, the circle is traced twice.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-parametric-conceptual-2">
    <title>Exercise 2: What is this curve?</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Consider the parametric equations <m>x=t^2</m>, <m>y=t+1</m>, for <m>-2\le t\le 2</m>. Which statement is true?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement><p>The curve is part of a parabola traced exactly once from left to right.</p></statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p>The curve is part of a sideways parabola, and some <m>x</m>-values occur more than once.</p></statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement><p>The curve is a line segment traced from bottom to top.</p></statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement><p>The curve is the entire parabola <m>y=x^2</m>.</p></statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    <solution>
      <p>Since <m>t=y-1</m>, substituting into <m>x=t^2</m> gives <m>x=(y-1)^2</m>, a sideways parabola. 
        Because <m>x=t^2</m>, the same <m>x</m>-value occurs for both positive and negative values of <m>t</m>.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise> -->

  <exercise xml:id="ex-parametric-conceptual-3">
    <title>Exercise 3: No Direction home</title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>Suppose <m>x(t)</m> is increasing and <m>y(t)</m> is decreasing on an interval. 
        What can be concluded about the motion of the particle <m>(x(t), y(t))</m> on that interval?</p>
      </statement>
      <choices>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement><p>The particle moves left and up.</p></statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement>
            <p>
              The particle moves right and down.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement><p>The particle moves left and down.</p></statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
          <statement><p>The particle must move along a straight line.</p></statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    <solution>
      <p>If <m>x(t)</m> is increasing, then the particle moves to the right. If <m>y(t)</m> is decreasing, then the particle moves downward. 
        This does not imply the path is a straight line.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>


  <exercise xml:id="ex-parametric-conceptual-4">
    <title>Exercise 4: Select the correct statement</title>
    
    <statement>
      <p>Two parametrizations are given:</p>
      <p><m>x=\cos t,\ y=\sin t,\ 0\le t\le 2\pi</m></p>
      <p>and</p>
      <p><m>x=\cos(2t),\ y=\sin(2t),\ 0\le t\le \pi</m>.</p>
      <p>Which statement is true?</p>
    </statement>
      <choices>
        <choice correct="no">
           <statement><p>The second traces a larger circle.</p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
           <statement><p>The second traces the same circle twice.</p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
           <statement><p>The second traces the same circle once, but at a different speed.</p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
           <statement><p>The two curves are different because the parameter intervals are different.</p> </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    <solution>
      <p>As <m>t</m> goes from <m>0</m> to <m>\pi</m>, the angle <m>2t</m> goes from <m>0</m> to <m>2\pi</m>. So the second parametrization traces the unit circle exactly once, but the parameter changes at a different rate.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-parametric-conceptual-5">
    <title>Exercise 5: Find the Cartesian Equation</title>
    <statement>
      <p>A parametric curve is given by <m>x=t^3</m>, <m>y=t^6</m>. Which Cartesian equation describes the curve?</p>
    </statement>
      <choices>
        <choice correct="no">
           <statement><p><m>y=x^2</m>, with <m>x\ge 0</m></p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
           <statement><p><m>y=x^2</m>, with <m>y\ge 0</m></p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
           <statement><p><m>x=y^2</m>, with <m>x\ge 0</m></p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
           <statement><p><m>y=x^3</m></p> </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    <solution>
       <statement>
      <p>Since <m>x=t^3</m>, we have <m>x^2=t^6=y</m>. Thus the curve satisfies <m>y=x^2</m>. 
        Because squares are nonnegative, <m>y\ge 0</m>, which is consistent with the parabola.</p>
       </statement>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-parametric-conceptual-6">
    <title>Exercise 6: Best in show</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Which statement best explains why two different parametric equations can describe the same geometric curve?</p>
    </statement>
      <choices>
        <choice correct="no">
           <statement><p>Because parametric equations always produce infinitely many different curves.</p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
           <statement><p>
            Different functions of the parameter can produce the same set of points, possibly with different speeds or directions.
           </p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
           <statement><p>Because every Cartesian equation has only one possible parametrization.</p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
           <statement><p>
            Because changing the parameter always changes the geometric shape of the curve.
          </p> </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    <solution>
       <statement>
      <p>
        A parametric curve is determined by the set of points traced and how they are traced. 
        Different choices of parameter can produce the same set of points while changing orientation, 
        speed, or how often the curve is retraced.
      </p>
       </statement>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="ex-parametric-conceptual-7">
    <title>Exercise 7: Correct Description</title>
    <statement>
      <p>A particle moves according to <m>x=\cos t</m>, <m>y=\sin t</m>, for <m>0\le t\le \pi</m>. 
        Which description is correct?</p>
    </statement>
      <choices>
        <choice correct="no">
           <statement><p>The particle traces the entire unit circle clockwise.</p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
           <statement><p>The particle traces the upper semicircle counterclockwise from <m>(1,0)</m> to <m>(-1,0)</m>.</p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
           <statement><p>The particle traces the lower semicircle clockwise from <m>(1,0)</m> to <m>(-1,0)</m>.</p> </statement>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="no">
           <statement><p>The particle traces a line segment from <m>(1,0)</m> to <m>(-1,0)</m>.</p> </statement>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    <solution>
       <statement>
      <p>At <m>t=0</m>, the point is <m>(1,0)</m>. At <m>t=\pi/2</m>, the point is <m>(0,1)</m>.
         At <m>t=\pi</m>, the point is <m>(-1,0)</m>. Thus the motion follows the upper semicircle counterclockwise.</p>
       </statement>
    </solution>
  </exercise>


<exercise label="parametric-multiple-choice-multiple-answers">
  <title>Exercise 8: Select all that apply</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A particle moves according to <m>x=t^2</m> and <m>y=t^2</m> for <m>-2\le t&lt;2</m>.
      Select all true statements about the curve and the motion of the particle.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <choices>
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Every point traced by the particle lies on the line <m>y=x</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Since <m>x=t^2</m> and <m>y=t^2</m>, we always have <m>y=x</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The particle traces a line segment from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(4,4)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. Because <m>t^2</m> ranges through all values from <m>0</m> to <m>4</m>, both <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> take the same values in that interval, so the traced set is exactly the line segment on <m>y=x</m> from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(4,4)</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice correct ="no"> 
      <statement>
        <p>
          The parametric equations trace an arc of the parabola <m>y=x^2</m> from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(4,4)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          This is false. Since <m>x=t^2</m> and <m>y=t^2</m>, eliminating the parameter gives <m>y=x</m>, not <m>y=x^2</m>. The curve is a line segment, not a parabolic arc.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The particle starts at <m>(4,4)</m>, moves to <m>(0,0)</m>, and then retraces the same segment back toward <m>(4,4)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. At <m>t=-2</m>, the particle is at <m>(4,4)</m>. As <m>t</m> increases to <m>0</m>, <m>t^2</m> decreases to <m>0</m>, so the particle moves to <m>(0,0)</m>. Then as <m>t</m> increases from <m>0</m> toward <m>2</m>, <m>t^2</m> increases again, so the particle retraces the same path.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice correct="no">
      <statement>
        <p>
          All points on the curve are traced twice.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          False. If <m>0&lt;a&lt;4</m>, then the point <m>(a,a)</m> occurs for both <m>t=\sqrt{a}</m> and <m>t=-\sqrt{a}</m>. 
          The origin is traced only once, at <m>t=0</m>. The point <m>(4,4)</m> is approached again as <m>t\to 2^-</m>, but <m>t=2</m> is not included.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The particle is at the point <m>(4, 4)</m> at some moment <m>t</m> .
        </p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          This is true. The particle is at the point <m>(4,4)</m> at time <m>t=-2</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
  <hint>
    <p>
      Try eliminating the parameter first. Then think separately about the <em>geometric curve</em> and the <em>direction of motion</em> as <m>t</m> increases.
    </p>
  </hint>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Since <m>x=t^2</m> and <m>y=t^2</m>, we have <m>y=x</m>. Because <m>-2\le t&lt;2</m>, the quantity <m>t^2</m> takes every value in the interval <m>[0,4]</m>. Therefore, the geometric curve is the line segment from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(4,4)</m>. At <m>t=-2</m>, the particle starts at <m>(4,4)</m>, moves toward <m>(0,0)</m> as <m>t</m> increases to <m>0</m>, and then retraces the segment back toward <m>(4,4)</m> as <m>t</m> increases from <m>0</m> toward <m>2</m>. Thus the true statements are that the curve lies on <m>y=x</m>, that it is the segment from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(4,4)</m>, that the particle retraces the segment, and that most points are traced twice.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>



<exercise xml:id="matching-parametric-distractors" label="matching-parametric-concepts-with-distractors">
  <title>Exercise 9: Match Parametric Equations to Graph Descriptions (with Distractors)</title>
  <idx>parametric matching</idx>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Match each parametric curve with the description of its graph or motion.
      Some responses may not match any curve.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <feedback>
    <p>
      Eliminate the parameter to see the geometric curve, consider the range of t, and pay attention to motion direction.
    </p>
  </feedback>
  <cardsort>
    <!-- True matches -->
    <match>
      <premise order="1"><m>x=t^2, y=t^2</m>, <m>-2 ≤ t &lt; 2</m></premise>
      <response>Line segment from (0,0) to (4,4), points mostly traced twice, retraces motion</response>
    </match>
    <match>
      <premise order="2"><m>x=cos(t), y=sin(t)</m>, <m>0 ≤ t ≤ 2π</m></premise>
      <response>Circle of radius 1 centered at the origin, traced once counterclockwise</response>
    </match>
    <match>
      <premise order="3"><m>x=t, y=t^2<m>, </m>-2 ≤ t ≤ 2</m></premise>
      <response>Parabola opening upward from (-2,2) to (2,2)</response>
    </match>
    <match>
      <premise order="4"><m>x=2cos(t), y=3sin(t)</m>, <m>0 ≤ t ≤ 2π</m></premise>
      <response>Ellipse centered at the origin, semi-major axis 3 along y, semi-minor axis 2 along x</response>
    </match>
    <match>
      <premise order="5"><m>x=sin(2t), y=cos(2t)</m>, <m>0 ≤ t ≤ 2π</m></premise>
      <response>Circle of radius 1 centered at the origin, traced twice counterclockwise</response>
    </match>
        <match>
      <premise order="6"><m>x=3, y=t^2</m>, <m>0 ≤ t ≤ 3</m></premise>
      <response>A vertical line segment</response>
    </match>
 <!-- Distractors -->
 
    <match>     
      <response>Line segment along <m>y=2x</m> from <m>(0,0)</m> to <m>(2,4)</m></response>
    </match>
    <match>
    <response>Circle of radius 2 centered at the origin</response>
    </match>
    <match>
            <response>An horizontal line segment</response>

    </match>
    <response>Downward-opening parabola from (-2,4) to (2,4)</response>
    <response>Horizontal line y=3</response>
    <response>Figure traced only once from t=0 to t=1</response>
  </cardsort>
</exercise>
</exercises>
</section>